│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation turns:\n  %t0 = sub nsw i8 0,    │
│ %x\n  %t1 = select i1 %c, i8 %x, i8 %t0\n  %t2 = sub i8 %y, %t1\ninto:\n  %1  │
│ = select i1 %c, i8 %t0, i8 %x\n  %t2 = add i8 %1, %y\nThis introduces poison: │
│ if %x == INT_MIN and %c == true, the source select chooses %x (non-poison)    │
│ while the target select chooses %t0 (poison due to nsw overflow). Alive2      │
│ confirms target is more poisonous than source.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's          │
│ Log:\nThe first (and only) transformation comes from InstCombine Negator:\n-  │
│ Negator sinks the negation of the select by swapping select arms because it   │
│ recognized the arms as negations of each other, and then rewrites sub into    │
│ add.\nThe log shows “successfully sunk negation into select” and the swapped  │
│ select is created. There is no other analysis involved (no AA pointers). The  │
│ error arises from this swap.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThere are two        │
│ related issues in Negator:\n- In visitImpl(), the special-case for select     │
│ swaps arms if isKnownNegation(Op1, Op2) holds. That predicate returns true    │
│ for pairs like (X, sub 0, X) regardless of overflow flags (NSW/NUW). Swapping │
│ is only semantics-preserving for representing \"-select(c,A,B)\" as           │
│ \"select(c,-A, -B)\" if choosing the swapped arm does not introduce poison    │
│ compared to computing -select. If the negated arm is sub nsw 0, X, selecting  │
│ it can produce poison that would not be produced by computing -select (which  │
│ would not use that arm when c selects the other arm). This is exactly the     │
│ failing case.\n- Independently, there is a general pattern “-(-(X)) -> X”     │
│ implemented as: if (match(V, m_Neg(m_Value(X)))) return X;. This ignores      │
│ overflow flags. If V is \"sub nsw 0, X\", then -(V) is poison when X =        │
│ INT_MIN, but returning X is not. So the pattern is invalid with               │
│ poison-generating flags.\n\nTherefore, the Negator incorrectly ignores poison │
│ semantics (NSW/NUW) when: (a) swapping select arms on known-negation arms,    │
│ and (b) simplifying double negation.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:    │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineNegator.cpp\n\nEdit point 1 (lines │
│ 133–141): Guard “-(-(X)) -> X” against nowrap flags. Only fold when the inner │
│ negate cannot produce poison (no NSW/NUW):\n\nReplace:\n  // -(-(X)) -> X.\n  │
│ if (match(V, m_Neg(m_Value(X))))\n    return X;\n\nWith:\n  // -(-(X)) -> X,  │
│ but only if the inner negation cannot produce poison\n  // (i.e. it must not  │
│ have NSW/NUW). Otherwise, -(poison) would be poison,\n  // and replacing it   │
│ with X would be wrong.\n  if (auto *InnerBO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(V))    │
│ {\n    if (InnerBO->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub &&\n                      │
│ match(InnerBO->getOperand(0), m_ZeroInt()) &&\n                               │
│ match(InnerBO->getOperand(1), m_Value(X))) {\n      auto *OBO =               │
│ cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(InnerBO);\n      if (!OBO->hasNoSignedWrap()  │
│ && !OBO->hasNoUnsignedWrap())\n        return X;\n    }\n  }\n\nEdit point 2  │
│ (lines 326–338): Make the select-arm swap only happen if both arms have no    │
│ NSW/NUW (so selecting either arm cannot introduce poison                      │
│ unexpectedly):\n\nReplace the block:\n  if (isKnownNegation(I->getOperand(1), │
│ I->getOperand(2), /*NeedNSW=*/false,\n                                        │
│ /*AllowPoison=*/false)) {\n    // Of one hand of select is known to be        │
