  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation turns:\n  %t0 =
sub nsw i8 0, %x\n  %t1 = select i1 %c, i8 %x, i8 %t0\n  %t2 = sub i8 %y,
%t1\ninto:\n  %1  = select i1 %c, i8 %t0, i8 %x\n  %t2 = add i8 %1, %y\nThis
introduces poison: if %x == INT_MIN and %c == true, the source select chooses %x
(non-poison) while the target select chooses %t0 (poison due to nsw overflow).
Alive2 confirms target is more poisonous than source.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nThe first (and only) transformation comes from InstCombine Negator:\n-
Negator sinks the negation of the select by swapping select arms because it
recognized the arms as negations of each other, and then rewrites sub into
add.\nThe log shows \u201csuccessfully sunk negation into select\u201d and the
swapped select is created. There is no other analysis involved (no AA pointers).
The error arises from this swap.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThere are two
related issues in Negator:\n- In visitImpl(), the special-case for select swaps
arms if isKnownNegation(Op1, Op2) holds. That predicate returns true for pairs
like (X, sub 0, X) regardless of overflow flags (NSW/NUW). Swapping is only
semantics-preserving for representing \"-select(c,A,B)\" as \"select(c,-A, -B)\"
if choosing the swapped arm does not introduce poison compared to computing
-select. If the negated arm is sub nsw 0, X, selecting it can produce poison that
would not be produced by computing -select (which would not use that arm when c
selects the other arm). This is exactly the failing case.\n- Independently, there
is a general pattern \u201c-(-(X)) -> X\u201d implemented as: if (match(V,
m_Neg(m_Value(X)))) return X;. This ignores overflow flags. If V is \"sub nsw 0,
X\", then -(V) is poison when X = INT_MIN, but returning X is not. So the pattern
is invalid with poison-generating flags.\n\nTherefore, the Negator incorrectly
ignores poison semantics (NSW/NUW) when: (a) swapping select arms on
known-negation arms, and (b) simplifying double negation.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineNegator.cpp\n\nEdit
point 1 (lines 133\u2013141): Guard \u201c-(-(X)) -> X\u201d against nowrap
flags. Only fold when the inner negate cannot produce poison (no
NSW/NUW):\n\nReplace:\n  // -(-(X)) -> X.\n  if (match(V, m_Neg(m_Value(X))))\n
return X;\n\nWith:\n  // -(-(X)) -> X, but only if the inner negation cannot
produce poison\n  // (i.e. it must not have NSW/NUW). Otherwise, -(poison) would
be poison,\n  // and replacing it with X would be wrong.\n  if (auto *InnerBO =
dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(V)) {\n    if (InnerBO->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub
&&\n        match(InnerBO->getOperand(0), m_ZeroInt()) &&\n
match(InnerBO->getOperand(1), m_Value(X))) {\n      auto *OBO =
cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(InnerBO);\n      if (!OBO->hasNoSignedWrap() &&
!OBO->hasNoUnsignedWrap())\n        return X;\n    }\n  }\n\nEdit point 2 (lines
326\u2013338): Make the select-arm swap only happen if both arms have no NSW/NUW
(so selecting either arm cannot introduce poison unexpectedly):\n\nReplace the
block:\n  if (isKnownNegation(I->getOperand(1), I->getOperand(2),
/*NeedNSW=*/false,\n                      /*AllowPoison=*/false)) {\n    // Of
one hand of select is known to be negation of another hand,\n    // just swap the
hands around.\n    auto *NewSelect = cast<SelectInst>(I->clone());\n    // Just
swap the operands of the select.\n    NewSelect->swapValues();\n    // Don't swap
prof metadata, we didn't change the branch behavior.\n
NewSelect->setName(I->getName() + \".neg\");\n    Builder.Insert(NewSelect);\n
return NewSelect;\n  }\n\nWith:\n  if (isKnownNegation(I->getOperand(1),
I->getOperand(2), /*NeedNSW=*/false,\n
/*AllowPoison=*/false)) {\n    // Swapping arms is only safe for representing
negation if neither arm\n    // can produce poison on selection due to nowrap
flags. Otherwise, we may\n    // expose poison on a path where -select would not
use that arm.\n    auto HasNoWrap = [](const Value *V) {\n      if (const auto
*OBO = dyn_cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V))\n        return
OBO->hasNoSignedWrap() || OBO->hasNoUnsignedWrap();\n      return false;\n
};\n    if (!HasNoWrap(I->getOperand(1)) && !HasNoWrap(I->getOperand(2))) {\n
auto *NewSelect = cast<SelectInst>(I->clone());\n      NewSelect->swapValues();\n
NewSelect->setName(I->getName() + \".neg\");\n      Builder.Insert(NewSelect);\n
return NewSelect;\n    }\n    // Otherwise, fall through and try general
recursive negation of both arms.\n  }\n\nThese changes ensure we do not perform
unsafe transformations in presence of NSW/NUW flags that can produce
poison.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug stems from Negator ignoring poison semantics
when simplifying negations: swapping select arms on negated pairs and eliminating
double negation without checking nowrap flags. The fix gates both transformations
on the absence of NSW/NUW flags so we do not introduce additional poison. This
prevents the incorrect transform in the reproducer, restoring correctness while
preserving the intended optimizations when safe.",
